An Onitsha Chief Magistrate Court 1 presided over by Her Lordship, Stella Emejulu Court Fails to Restrain Market Union from Collecting Levy yesterday failed to grant an order over a case brought by some traders under a union, ESDA from Ochanja Central Market, Onitsha The traders, Godwin Eze, Emenike Nwosu and Chinedu Okonkwo had approached the court to stop the union (ESDA) from collecting any form of levy from traders under its union. It is believed that the plaintiffs are being fronted by a billionaire trader in the union, Chief Nwabueze Umeh who was once the Chairman of the union. Unlawful Suspension: Court Grants OGFZAA Manager’s Plea To… Slain Akwa Ibom Jobseeker: Accused Person Denies Police… After a complaint by the plaintiffs’ counsel, Bar. A.E Okwulehie that the defendants’ counsel, Nnazimuzo Ugorji filed a preliminary objection very late which the defence counsel said was not intentional. The court, however, granted the excuse and adjourned the matter to April 13 this year. The plaintiffs had dragged the union Chairman and Secretary, Mssrs Leonard Umeh and Obinna Nnubia to court seeking an end to such exercise by the court. In an interview shortly after the sitting, the defence counsel, Mr Ugorji said that the court’s failure to continue proceeding on the matter in court as earlier stated means that the union leadership should continue collecting their levy until the determination of the court on the matter. A Patron in the union, Obed Offer commended the judiciary for a transparent proceeding. ESDA Chairman, Chief Leonard Umeh expressed hope in the court process, adding that the judiciary remains the last hope of the common man.